				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$q_\text{ide} = \frac{q}{1 - r}$$\end{document}where qide is the theoretical maximum output, q is the energy output under the current mining conditions, and r is the gas loss rate during the CSG extraction process (in %). Bai et al. (2001), Li and Sun (2008), and Zhou and Zhang (2011) found r values for the Fanzhuang block of 41%, 50%, and 46%, respectively. The average value of their results is 45.7%, which is used here. Figure 3 shows q. Therefore, qide can be estimated by Eq. (14). When calculating the EROI, q and qide are directly converted to heat units using the values in Table 2.Table 2
